  "learnings_before": "- Both valproate and carbamazepine are guideline‑consistent first‑line options for focal seizures in children ≤ 2 years; selection is guided by drug availability, tolerability, and the need for laboratory monitoring.\n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) are acceptable for focal epilepsy but must be avoided in any child with a documented drug‑induced rash or hypersensitivity.\n- Before any change of therapy, clinicians must obtain baseline safety labs (ALT/AST < 2 × ULN, platelet count > 150 × 10⁹/L, ammonia within normal limits) and, when feasible, a serum level of the current AED.\n- Dose optimisation is performed first: if the current dose is < 20 mg/kg/day for valproate or < 15 mg/kg/day for carbamazepine and seizure control is suboptimal, the dose should be titrated upward in 25‑50 mg increments every 1–2 weeks before considering drug substitution or adjuncts.\n- Exaggerated startles, feeding difficulty, or increased tone in children with cerebral palsy are not automatically attributed to drug toxicity; they require confirmation (e.g., seizure diary or video‑EEG) before altering the regimen.\n- The decision hierarchy is: (1) confirm seizure‑free status (≥ 6 months) and adherence ≥ 80 %; (2) verify normal safety labs; (3) maintain the current regimen unchanged; (4) if either seizure control or labs are inadequate, proceed to dose optimisation; (5) if optimisation fails, consider switching to valproate (after normal LFTs) or adding levetiracetam as an adjunct.\n- Valproate is stocked in >90 % of district pharmacies at ≈ $0.08 per 100 mg; carbamazepine is similarly stocked at ≈ $0.05 per 100 mg; levetiracetam is 2–3 × more expensive and often unavailable, so it is reserved for documented valproate intolerance or failure.\n- Phenobarbital is reserved for refractory cases or when both valproate and levetiracetam are unavailable; it may be used in spastic cerebral palsy only with close monitoring for sedation, otherwise it is avoided.\n- Initiation of valproate requires baseline liver function tests and ammonia; if ALT/AST > 2 × ULN or ammonia is elevated, valproate should be deferred and an alternative AED chosen.\n- When a child is seizure‑free on a stable valproate dose within the therapeutic window (20–30 mg/kg/day) and safety labs are normal, the protocol mandates continuation of the exact current dose without escalation or adjunct addition.",
  "candidate_learnings": "- Carbamazepine is the default first‑line AED for focal seizures in Ugandan children and adolescents because it is on the Essential Medicines List, stocked in >90 % of district pharmacies, and costs ≈ $0.05 per 100 mg.\n- Valproate is the preferred first‑line AED for generalized seizures; it is also widely stocked (≈ $0.08 per 100 mg) and used when carbamazepine is contraindicated or unavailable.\n- Dual therapy with carbamazepine + valproate is common in patients with mixed focal‑generalized epilepsy or in children with cerebral palsy, especially when each drug targets a different seizure component and lower doses are used for each.\n- Phenobarbital is reserved for refractory epilepsy or when both carbamazepine and valproate are unavailable; its use is limited due to sedation risk and higher toxicity in malnourished children.\n- Levetiracetam is prescribed only after documented failure or intolerance to carbamazepine/valproate, because it is 2–3 × more expensive and frequently out of stock in district hospitals.\n- Dose optimization is initiated when the current dose is below the therapeutic lower bound (carbamazepine < 10 mg/kg/day; valproate < 20 mg/kg/day); titration is done in 5 mg/kg increments every 1–2 weeks with clinical monitoring.\n- Laboratory monitoring (baseline CBC, LFTs, serum sodium, ammonia for valproate) is often unavailable; in the absence of reported abnormal labs, clinicians assume results are within normal limits for decision‑making.\n- Adherence ≥ 80 % is a critical determinant of seizure control; non‑adherence is addressed first with caregiver counseling before any medication change.\n- When a patient is seizure‑free for ≥ 6 months, adherent, and has presumed normal labs, the protocol mandates continuation of the exact current regimen without dose escalation or addition of new agents.\n- In children with cerebral palsy, increased tone or feeding difficulty is not automatically attributed to AED toxicity; confirmed seizure diaries or video‑EEG are required before modifying therapy.\n- Cost and availability drive drug choice: clinicians prioritize the cheapest, locally stocked AEDs and only consider higher‑cost options (e.g., levetiracetam, topiramate) for documented refractory cases.\n- For infants ≤ 2 years, valproate is avoided when possible due to hepatic risk; carbamazepine is preferred if no rash or hypersensitivity history exists.\n- Ethosuximide is used exclusively for typical absence seizures and should be discontinued if the seizure type is focal or generalized tonic‑clonic.\n- Drug‑drug interactions are monitored: valproate can raise carbamazepine levels; clinicians check for hepatotoxicity when both are used together and adjust doses accordingly.",
